Now let's start our drawing by putting a line across the bottom part of the picture like this, about a fourth of the way up.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:16,000
And then let's draw another one that sort of curves and dips down here, and another one here, so that we create some foothills.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:23,000
And a mountain back here. You know, this is going to be a scene of one of my favorite spots, Palm Springs, California,

4
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:29,000
where the snow-capped mountains meet the palm trees and the grapefruit roads.

5
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Now let's put in a little tone up here in the sky. Place your pencil on its side.

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Or if you have a crayon, use a broad side so that you can cover a lot of area with a few strokes.

7
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Lay it in rather lightly. We don't want our sky to come too dark.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,000
However, we're going to get a snow-capped peak there, so we do need little depth to this.

9
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:58,000
After you've covered most of it, you can smoothly blend it by using a piece of cleansing tissue.

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Show you how that's done. You just bunch it up like this, and then you work it back and forth,

11
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:10,000
and work it in various directions until you get the background smoothed out.

12
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:17,000
That's the idea. Of course, if you want to put in a cloud effect, well, you can add some more tone to it later.

13
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:25,000
And now let's get that snow-capped to the mountain. Let's bring it down here sort of irregularly, like that.

14
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:34,000
And bring some tone down this slope, because that mountain is basically a cone form.

15
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
We'll have our light come in from the upper right, so you'd shade down the left side like that.

16
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Bring your tone right down close to the top of this foothill.

17
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Now let's get a crevice in this mountain, sort of a big canyon. Make another one go out this way.

18
00:01:50,000 --> 00:02:01,000
Use your crayon on its side like that so you sort of craze it and break it up into sort of triangular shapes.

19
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:08,000
A little bit later, we'll put in a few accents in those canyons to indicate more roughness.

20
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Of course, here and there you can blend across in order to give a little more substance and tone,

21
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:20,000
